"Abstract Telecommunications fraud is often considered to be victimless. Most telcos, particularly ex-government monopolies, are usually cash rich and the common conception is that they can afford to take a hit. Is this true? Closer inspection tells us not. Fraud can cause distress, loss of service and loss of customer confidence. Moreover, if a telco takes a substantial fraud hit then it is almost inevitably passed on to the customer in the long run. Telecommunications crime is not some latter day Robin Hood activity committed by loveable rogues. Rather, it is a serious business which causes real harm. Some estimates of global telecommunications fraud losses run to some $30 billion per annum."
